<HEADLINE> Joint Syrian-Iraqi Committee Meets in Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Syrian-Iraqi Committee
met for the first time in 20 years here Saturday, chaired by Syrian
Economy Minister Mohammed al Imadi and his Iraqi counterpart
Mohammad Mehdi Salah.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the committee discussed means of developing
economic and trade relations between both countries in the context
of the U.N. resolutions, according to the Syrian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue discussions through their technical
sub-committee made up for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to study several issues, including
boosting trade exchange, developing economic relations, re-
activating technical and cultural relations and completing talks on
cooperation in the field of transport.
</P>
<P>
They will consider particularly the exploitation of railway
links between the two countries and the use of Syria's
Mediterranean ports of Lattaquieh and Tartus for Iraq's imports and
exports. An agreement has already been signed on Iraq's importing
million tons of goods via Tartus this year.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between the two neighbors has not risen to the
expected level, as Syrian exports to Iraq hit 400 million U.S.
dollar only after the U.N. oil-for-food program was launched,
compared to over 1 billion dollars of goods exported to Iraq by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria backed Iran in its eight-year bloody war with Iraq in the
1980s. But Baghdad-Damascus relations began to improve in 1997.
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad Said al-Sahaf paid two visits to
Syria in late June and early July and was received by the new
president, Bashar al-Assad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
