<HEADLINE> Brisk Tourism Raises Gold Demand in UAE, Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Brisk tourism in the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and Saudi Arabia has boosted gold demand in the two
countries, showed a latest report issued by Dubai Chamber of
Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The report said that UAE has witnessed a flourishing tourism in
recent years, particularly in Dubai, which is considered to be the
biggest gold importer in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Gold Council (WGC), over 90 percent of
the 1.5-2 million tourists coming to Dubai each year end up with
buying gold.
</P>
<P>
The more than 5 million pilgrims to Saudi Arabia every year for
the Haj and Umrah, most of them coming from the subcontinent,
southeast Asia and Africa, also make Saudi gold market fizz.
</P>
<P>
Saudi authorities expect 10 million tourists and pilgrims this
year, which will further stimulate gold and jewellery consumption
there.
</P>
<P>
"The Saudis tend to use this large number of pilgrims to the
very best possible way by introducing new products with religious
designs," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE ranks 13th regarding annual demand for gold at 79.7 tons
while Saudi Arabia comes fourth at 199 tons, behind India, the U.S.
and China.
</P>
<P>
The report also said gold bars and coins are exempted from an
import tax while finished and semi-finished gold and jewellery are
levied a 12 percent tax Saudi Arabia and a 1.5-4 percent in the
UAE. But neither have sales tax on the metal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
