<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, August 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Intense controversy over amendment of the press law on
Sunday erupted between members of Iran's Majlis(parliament), almost
leading to physical encounters in an open session of the
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The clashes broke out following an announcement by Majlis
speaker Mehdi Karrubi that a motion to debate the press law has
been withdrawn from the agenda of the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
The press law was amended by the conservative-controlled fifth
Majlis in April to put more restrictions on the press. (Iran-Press
Law)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak told the cabinet
on Sunday that he expected a number of Lebanese security units to
arrive at the border with Israel in the first stage, rather than
the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
The units would establish a Lebanese military presence in the
southern part of that country, following the major deployment of
the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) throughout the region
and along the border with Israel on Saturday. (Israel-Lebanon-
Border)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak reshuffled his
cabinet Sunday morning, naming four of his ministers to hold
concurrent posts.
</P>
<P>
At Sunday morning's weekly cabinet meeting, Communications
Minister Binyamin Ben Eliezer took up the Construction and Housing
Minister post, while Minister in Prime Minister's Office Haim Ramon
also got an additional portfolio of Interior Minister. (Israel-
Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Sunday that
he thought conditions for a second Israeli-Palestinian summit talks
for reaching a peace agreement are premature.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the cabinet meeting on Sunday, Barak said that it is
still too early to determine whether the Palestinians are ready to
achieve progress in the peace process, officials in Barak's office
said. (Israel-Palestine-Next Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Brisk tourism in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and
Saudi Arabia has boosted gold demand in the two countries, showed a
latest report issued by Dubai Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The report said that UAE has witnessed a flourishing tourism in
recent years, particularly in Dubai, which is considered to be the
biggest gold importer in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Gold Council (WGC), over 90 percent of
the 1.5-2 million tourists coming to Dubai each year end up with
buying gold. (UAE-Tourism-Gold) 
