<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Cargo Ship for International Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The rocket with the supply ship blasted off from the Baikonur
cosmodrome in Kazakhstan at 10:27 p.m. Moscow time (1827 GMT), and
was smoothly put into its pre-determined orbit at 10:36 p.m.
Moscow time (1836 GMT), Interfax cited the Russian Aerospace
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cargo ship was lifted into space by the Soyuz-U in
accordance with launch calculations done by the agency. It was
launched in preparation for a long-term expedition to ISS
scheduled to begin October 30.
</P>
<P>
This is the first unmanned cargo flight to the ISS. Mission
Control in the town of Korolyov outside Moscow has been instructed
to control the flight and Progress' docking maneuvers with the
first ISS elements already in orbit.
</P>
<P>
The basic cargo is fuel reserves to be used for correcting the
orbit of the previously linked ISS modules Zarya-Unity-Zvezda,
which are in an orbit with a 380-kilometer apogee and a 352-
kilometer perigee, said the Mission Control.
</P>
<P>
The similar parameters for the pre-determined working orbit of
the ISS are 460 and 410 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Progress M1-3 will deliver to the ISS 2,434.2 kilograms of
cargo, including 1,559.4 kilograms of fuel and oxidizer for
raising the station's orbit, plus 260 kilograms of fuel for
ensuring the station's orientation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the cargo ship is to bring to the station
scientific equipment and instruments to back up the station's on-
board systems, including flight guidance and navigation systems,
the electricity and heat supply network, gas and water tanks for
the ISS as well as linen, personal hygiene effects and individual
protection, and on-board technical manuals.
</P>
<P>
This is also the third launch of the newly modified version of
a cargo ship in the Progress M1 series, the so-called "space truck.
" The first ship was launched for the Russian orbital complex Mir
on February 1, the second on April 26 this year.
</P>
<P>
The docking of Progress M1 with the first elements of the
International Space Station has been scheduled for 00:14 a.m.
Moscow time on August 9 (2014 GMT on August 8).
</P>
<P>
The Russian space agency's press service has said that yet
another two short-term missions to ISS by U.S. space shuttles and
a Russian Progress M1-4 cargo ship are planned as part of
preparations for the first long-term expedition to the
International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
Five American astronauts and two Russian cosmonauts will set
out on expedition STS-106 aboard the space shuttle Atlantis to the
ISS on September 8.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis will deliver to the station a double cargo module, and
the crew will shift the cargo from the shuttle and Progress M1-3
over to the ISS. This expedition is scheduled to last until
September 19.
</P>
<P>
Yet, another Russian Progress M1-4 cargo ship is due to lift
off for the station on September 14, and on September 28 an U.S.-
Japanese crew are to set out on expedition STS-92 aboard the
Discovery space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
Now American astronaut William Sheered and Russian cosmonauts,
ship Commander Yuri Gidzenko and flight engineer Sergei Krikalev
are training for a four-month expedition aboard a Russian ship
Soyuz TM, scheduled for October 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
