<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Social Fund for Development has acquired a
total of 1.89 billion Egyptian pounds (540 million U.S. dollars)
for this fiscal year starting July 1, Hussein el-Gammal, director-
general of the fund said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The fund board of directors held a meeting in the day to review
its resources, of which 1.27 billion pounds (over 360 million
dollars) have been allocated as loans to youths for starting or
expanding business, 480 million pounds (140 million dollars) for
public projects and the rest for technical services, el-Gammal said
</P>
<P>
The directors also discussed ways to upgrade the fund's
efficiency through introduction of modern technology, in line with
new orientations of donor states and corporations, he added.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to set up a network of health compounds in 1,000
Egyptian villages at a cost of 400 million pounds (110 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The number of Burger King fast-food restaurants have
reached 100 throughout Turkey since first was opened in 1995,
reported the Anatolia News Agency on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Burger King General Director Alp Gurdil told reporters in
Istanbul Sunday that they are planning to open 300 restaurants all
over the country by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Gurdil said that Burger King restaurants in Turkey has the
highest rate of increase compared to those in Europe, Africa and
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two restaurants, opened in International
Flights Terminal at Istanbul's Ataturk Airport, have are proved to
be a success.
</P>
<P>
Burger King, which was founded in 1954, has over 11,000
restaurants in 58 countries around the world.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Abu Dhabi Oil Refining Company (Takreer), a
subsidiary of the Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (ADNOC) has
announced that its second production train for condensate
processing at Ruwais refinery would go on stream this week,
according to a report in Sunday's "Takreer News".
</P>
<P>
The report said production capacity would be at 140,000 barrels
per day. The first production train that was launched in May has
raised its producing capacity from original 100,000 barrels per day
to the current 140,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
The total capacity of the two production trains will reach 280,
000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of condensate processing will assist the
refinery in meeting market requirements. It will increase the
refinery's ability to process condensate via two identical
processing trains, the report added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The 10th Egyptian products exhibition will be staged in
the Red Sea city of Jeddah, Saudi Arabia on August 30, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During the eight-day event, more than 70 firms will display
products including foodstuff, engineering, agricultural and
chemical products, Mustafa Nofel, commercial attache at the
Egyptian embassy in Riyadh said.
</P>
<P>
Nofel said that deals worth 100 million U.S. dollars are
expected to be sealed at the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
A symposium will also be held for Egyptian and Saudi businessmen
to discuss establishment of joint ventures in the fields of
industry, tourism, financial services and real estate, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
