<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Calls for Total Cancellation of Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) heads of state Sunday gathered in
Windhoek, Namibia with calls for the total scrapping of debt in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of this year's summit meeting,
outgoing SADC chairman and Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano
said five SADC member countries, namely Mozambique, Angola, Zambia,
Tanzania and Malawi, are experiencing acute debt problems.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in Mozambique the external debt per head is
almost seven times the gross national product per capita, while
Zambia in the 1990s has spent more than 30 percent of its national
budget on debt repayment and only 10 percent on social services.
</P>
<P>
This dire situation deserves immediate attention from creditor
nations and international financial institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "improved economic prospects can only come
into reality in the SADC countries, in Africa and in the
developing world at large if the current economically debilitating
debt is forgiven in its totality."
</P>
<P>
The SADC heads of state will meet in a closed session Monday
morning to discuss the conflict in the democratic Republic of the
Congo, give green light to the revised SADC free trade pact and
several other minor protocols and approve a regional position on
acceptance of western drug companies' lower price offers on AIDS
drugs.
</P>
<P>
Another key issue at the meeting will be the restructuring of
SADC, including SADC's controversial security organ now headed by
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
