<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Calls for Renewed Peace Efforts in Congo and Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) heads of state Sunday gathered in
Windhoek, Namibia calling for renewed peace efforts in the war-
torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and Angola.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of this year's summit meeting,
outgoing SADC chairman and Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano
said moves to revive the faltering DRC peace talks are dealt a
blow by DRC President Laurent Kabila's boycott of the summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
General-Secretary of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
Salim Ahmed Salim and presidents of Seychelles and Mauritius were
also absent from the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
SADC is gravely concerned about the situation in the DRC and
Angola and is working closely with the OAU and the United Nations
to end the conflicts, Chissano said.
</P>
<P>
He said the humanitarian situation in the two countries is also
a matter of grave concern, where thousands of people have been
displaced.
</P>
<P>
"These people are condemned to die of hunger and deprivation
unless assistance is provided as a matter of urgency. Once again
we would like to appeal to the magnanimity of the international
community to provide the much-needed humanitarian assistance," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to throw SADC's weight behind beleaguered
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe when he said the former heroes
of freedom struggle in that country are now being wrongly labeled
as anti-democratic and "even dictators".
</P>
<P>
"We can not in SADC condone these views. We are the democrats
and we want democracy to work according to the will of our people
in each one of our countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The SADC heads of state will meet in a closed session Monday
morning to discuss the DRC conflict, give green light to the
revised SADC free trade pact and several other minor protocols and
approve a regional position on acceptance of western drug
companies' lower price offers on AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
Another key issue at the meeting will be the restructuring of
SADC, including SADC's controversial security organ headed by
Mugabe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Insists Burundi Peace Deal be Signed in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Burundian peace facilitator,
former South African president Nelson Mandela still maintains that
the peace agreement aimed at ending the seven-year ethnic civil
war in Burundi will be signed on its scheduled date of August 28
despite the recent announcement by key warring parties that they
will not sign the accord.
</P>
<P>
Mark Bomani, Mandela's top aid and leader of the mediation team,
said here on Sunday that when meeting with Burundian President
Pierre Buyoya this weekend in Johannesburg, South Africa, Mandela
reaffirmed that the signing of the peace deal will take place at
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
"The facilitator will like the negotiating parties to come with
a consensus on all the four issues (they are negotiating about),
or some of them, and it is hoped that the revised document will be
embodied in the
final agreement for signing on August 28," Bomani said.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the 19 Burundian negotiating parties and groups will
meet in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha beginning on Monday to
resolve the four outstanding issues they still disagree.
</P>
<P>
Whether or not the scheduled signing of the peace deal on
August 28 will come true is set to be known at the end of the
Arusha meeting, which is expected to clear the ground for the
power-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
According to Bomani, the core issues on which the parties are
expected to focus include the electoral system, the leadership of
the proposed transitional government, questions concerning the
guarantees where things are not clear, and the integration of
armed rebel groups into the government forces.
</P>
<P>
Mandela circulated a draft peace plan three weeks ago in Arusha,
but the main Hutu rebel group in Burundi, the CNDD-FDD (the
National Council for the Defense of Democracy - Forces for the
Defense of Democracy) announced that it will not sign the peace
agreement because they had not been involved in the peace talks
since it began two years ago.
</P>
<P>
A day later, Buyoya's military government declared in Bujumbura
that it too will not sign the accord unless a cease-fire agreement
is signed first and Buyoya is allowed to preside over the
transitional government.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft accord, the Tutsi minority, which has dominated
Burundi's political and economic life since independence, would
have to hand over power to a democratically elected government in
three years' time.
</P>
<P>
At least 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed
since fighting in the tiny central African country began in
October 1993 when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the country's
first democratically elected president Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader Meets Arafat on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Ghaddafi held
talks in capital Tripoli on Sunday with visiting Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat on the developments of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to Libyan News Agency, Arafat briefed Ghaddafi on the
latest developments in the peace process, including the collapsed
Camp David summit between him and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Tripoli earlier on Sunday as part of his tour
of Arab and foreign countries to explain the Palestinian positions
and rally international support for Palestinian dealing with Israel
in peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Arafat left Libya Sunday afternoon to continue his trip to the
United Arab Emirates. He has visited France, Saudi Arabia, Yemen,
Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Sudan, Egypt, South Africa and Turkey,
and is expected to visit Russia on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
