<HEADLINE> Second Israeli-Palestinian Summit Premature: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Sunday that he thought conditions for a second Israeli-
Palestinian summit talks for reaching a peace agreement are
premature.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the cabinet meeting on Sunday, Barak said that it is
still too early to determine whether the Palestinians are ready to
achieve progress in the peace process, officials in Barak's office
said.
</P>
<P>
Assessing the current situation after having talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on Thursday, Barak said that in his
opinion, Arab states will not pressure Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat to make further concessions.
</P>
<P>
However, these countries may act as safety net for Arafat if
Israel and the Palestinians finally come to an agreement, said
Barak.
</P>
<P>
Early Sunday, there were Israeli media speculations that Israeli
and Palestinian negotiators were holding secret talks and preparing
for another summit following the botched Camp David summit talks
last month.
</P>
<P>
The Camp David talks, hosted by U.S. President Bill Clinton,
failed to resolve core issues, especially the status of Jerusalem
and the right of Palestinian refugees to return to their homeland,
to lay grounds for a permanent peace deal between Israel and the
Palesnitians by September.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has since launched a campaign to gain support for
Palestinian cause by visiting France, Saudi Arabia, Morocco,
Tunisia, Algeria, Egypt, Turkey and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
To counteract Arafat's move, Barak announced Sunday that he will
dispatch two of his confidants to a number of countries to
expatiate Israel's views regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, who also holds the
Transport portfolio, will visit Russia, Germany and Turkey in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, a possible
candidate to replace David Levy as foreign Minister, will visit
Britain, France, Portugal, Spain, Belgium and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Levy resigned from his post last Wednesday and took leave of his
senior ministry staff on Sunday by vehemently criticizing Barak's
approach in handling the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
