<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Awarded SADC Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president Nelson Mandela was on Sunday awarded the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) Sir Seretse Khama SADC Medal.
</P>
<P>
The medal, for people who have made outstanding contributions
towards achieving the regional organization's goals, was presented
to Mandela at the two-day SADC heads of state summit meeting which
opened in Windhoek, Namibia on Sunday afternoon, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Mandela received the medal for his role in promoting peace in
SADC and Africa as a whole and for his leadership of South Africa
after the 1994 democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is also recognized for leading the South African people
in "their heroic struggle against apartheid and colonial
domination", SADC said.
</P>
<P>
The previous recipients of the award, established in 1985, were
four former presidents, namely Julius Nyerere of Tanzania,
Ketumile Masire of Botswana, Agostino Neto of Angola and Samora
Machel of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Asked on his arrival at Windhoek's Eros airport earlier on
Sunday what he thought SADC should do about the ongoing conflict
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Mandela said SADC has
highly capable leaders who are able to address and resolve the
problems facing the region.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on whether he has spoken to SADC leaders on a
request by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat that he mediate in the
Middle East peace process, Mandela said "it's not very good when
you are dealing with heads of state to announce what you are doing
or propose to do with the press."
</P>
<P>
"Respect for heads of state means that we should give them the
privilege of knowing what we are doing and then in due course we
can involve the press," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
