<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders Urged to Step up Peace Efforts in Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president Nelson Mandela Sunday urged southern African leaders to
redouble their efforts to bring peace and stability to the region.
</P>
<P>
Accepting the prestigious Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Sir Seretse Khama Medal at the opening of this
year's SADC heads of state summit meeting in Windhoek, Namibia,
Mandela said it was with sadness that he noted parts of the region
were still struggling under destructive conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Once more, those who suffer most cruelly under these conflicts
are the ordinary citizens, and especially the most vulnerable,
namely the women and children," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "it is incumbent upon us to redouble our
efforts to bring peace and stability to our entire region so that
our people can develop to the full their human potential and live
lives of dignity."
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the collective wisdom of
leadership in the region will bring a speedy and lasting end to
those conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
