<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Deal Firmly With Unruly Students: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Higher Education and
Technology Minister Herbert Murerwa Sunday said his ministry will
deal firmly with unruly students disrupting learning at
institutions.
</P>
<P>
College students should appreciate the contributions that both
parents and taxpayers are making in funding their education, the
minister said while officiating at the graduation ceremony of
about 500 students of the United College of Education in Bulawayo,
the country's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
He said it is unfair for students to engage in demonstrations
without appreciating that the government is providing them with
quality education at highly subsidized rates.
</P>
<P>
"These students fail to appreciate their privileged status
compared with the majority of students in the country who are in
private colleges where no such government support is available,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged disciplined students to brush aside
intimidation by the unruly elements, saying "my ministry will deal
firmly with these unruly elements."
</P>
<P>
The ministry has recently closed Harare Polytechnic, Harare
Institute of Technology and Gweru Polytechnic following violent
demonstrations there against the proposed privatization of
catering services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
