<HEADLINE> Syria Wants Just, Comprehensive Peace: Assad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bashar al-Assad said on
Sunday that Syria wants to achieve just and comprehensive peace
according to U.N. resolutions, and it is willing to resume Middle
East peace talks when Israel is ready.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during a meeting with Edward Walker, U.S.
assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs, at the
People's Palace here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Walker is the first U.S. official to visit Syria since Assad was
sworn in as president on July 10 following the death of his father,
Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Walker arrived Sunday morning in Damascus, the fifth leg of his
Middle East tour, which has taken him to Egypt, Saudi Arabia,
Jordan and Tunisia since the failed Camp David summit between
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and the Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on July 25.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting was Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk
Shareh, who had held talks with Walker earlier on the current
situation in the Middle East and the future of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Briefing Shareh on the "results" of the summit, Walker was
trying, as he did all the way, to convince Arab leaders of the
necessity of flexibility in dealing with Israel, especially in the
Jerusalem issue and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that Shareh insisted "Any peaceful
solution should be fair and comprehensive, ensure the full Israeli
withdrawal from the occupied Arab territories to the borders of
June 4, 1967, and guarantee the rights of the Palestinian people."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need for Israel to withdraw from Arab East
Jerusalem and for the guarantee of legitimate national rights of
the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiations between Syria and Israel have stalled since
January. Damascus demanded a full withdrawal of Israeli troops from
the Golan Heights they captured in 1967, which was rejected by the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel feared such a withdrawal would give the Syrians access to
the Sea of Galilee, thus endangering its main source of fresh
water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
