<HEADLINE> Falcons From UAE Released in Northern Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- As many as 111 falcons sent by
President Shaikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al Nahyan of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) were released in Gilgit and Hunza valleys recently,
the Associated Press of Pakistan reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The falcons were airlifted from Abu Dhabi in a special aircraft
to Gilgit.
</P>
<P>
The release of falcons was jointly organized by the UAE
Environmental Research and Wildlife Development Agency and the
Falcon Foundation of Pakistan under a Falcon Release Project.
</P>
<P>
The project's aim is to resuscitate the depleting falcon
population for which the northern areas of Pakistan are considered
an ideal habitat by international wildlife experts.
</P>
<P>
Gilgit had been the site of earlier releases in 1996 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
These falcons were released 130 kilometers north of Gilgit
where sufficient water and food are available.
</P>
<P>
Generally an area with a radius of five kilometers, having food
and water, can easily sustain one falcon.
</P>
<P>
These falcons will be an added attraction for tourists from all
over the world in the most fascinating northern areas of Pakistan,
known for their majestic peaks, wildlife and natural environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
