<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel to Set Up Internet Exchange Center in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp will set up its first
Internet exchange architectural development center in Beijing
later this year.
</P>
<P>
The move is to accelerate the development of networking and
communications solutions in China, said Tom Franz, vice-president
and general manager of the network processing group with Intel
Group.
</P>
<P>
"This is another clear demonstration of the company's support
for Chinese customers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Intel Internet exchange architecture is a framework for
designing powerful and flexible networking and telecommunications
equipment using re-programmable silicon, which allows systems
designers to add network functionality cost-effectively.
</P>
<P>
As part of the Internet exchange architecture, Intel has
introduced a developer's tool kit to help facilitate product
design and enable equipment suppliers to provide post-sale product
enhancements to their customers.
</P>
<P>
"Through the use of standard software interfaces, programmable
silicon and readily available development tools, Intel and out
customers can look forward to ushering in a new era of networking,
" Franz said.
</P>
<P>
New capabilities, such as wire-speed voice, video and data
services, can be added to existing equipment simply by
reprogramming the network processor, which allows suppliers to
extend the life and value of their designs.
</P>
<P>
Many domestic telecom companies have shown interest in the
project. "The technology level of application specific integrated
circuit in China has lagged, said a representative of Huawei, one
of the four non-state telecom companies in China.
</P>
<P>
"Intel Internet exchange architecture provides us with an
opportunity to catch up with the world-class development trend,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
