<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bayliss Wins Opening Race in Superbike Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Australian Troy Bayliss, replacing
injured champion Carl Fogarty, won the opening race of the 10th
round of the superbike world championship in Brands Hatch, England
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Compatriot Troy Corser, on an Aprilia, cut Colin Edwards's
championship lead to 14 points after finishing sixth while the
American came 10th on his spare Honda.
</P>
<P>
Edwards totalled 271 points, Corser 257 and Japan's Noriyuki
Haga 243 after finishing fifth.
</P>
<P>
Edwards won both races at Brands Hatch last year and led at the
end of the first lap.
</P>
<P>
But he was clearly struggling after being involved in a four-
rider crash at the first bend in the red-flagged first attempt to
get the race started.
</P>
<P>
While he and championship rival Noriyuki Haga escaped injury,
Briton Steve Hislop suffered a suspected fracture of the left
wrist and right ankle after being hit by his bouncing bike in the
gravel trap.
</P>
<P>
Bayliss led the re-started 25-lap race on the works Ducati by
clocking 36 minutes 35.753 seconds. It was Bayliss's second win of
the season since he was drafted in to replace the injured Fogarty.
</P>
<P>
Neil Hodgson of Britain finished second with 36:35.988 and his
compatriot Chris Walker was third in 36:44.535. 
</P>
</TEXT>
