<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Clergyman Honored for Recording Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- This east China city has built a
library named after a U.S. clergyman who risked his life filming
Japanese soldiers' atrocities here in 1937.
</P>
<P>
John Magge filmed massacre scenes with a film camera when the
city fell to the Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
The 105 minutes of film footage is strong evidence of the
Nanjing Massacre, in which more than 300,000 Chinese were brutally
killed by Japanese soldiers, historians say.
</P>
<P>
The massacre shocked the world, but there are some Japanese who
attempt to deny it.
</P>
<P>
Historians say that Magge's film footage is the only film
record of the Nanjing Massacre that has been discovered so far.
</P>
<P>
In 1958, the church in Xiaguan District where Magge preached
was turned into a secondary school library. The local government
has now named it the John Magge Library. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
