<HEADLINE> Philippines to Pour More Money Into Education Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
build nearly 8,200 new classrooms in public schools next year at a
total cost of 3.2 billion pesos (about 73 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new funding will address 30 percent of the current shortage
of some 25,800 classrooms nationwide, according to a report of the
Philippines News Agency Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted House Majority Leader Eduardo Gullas as
saying the 3.2 billion pesos funding for the School Building
Program in the proposed 2001 national budget is 1.2 billion pesos
(about 27 million dollars) or 60 percent higher than the
allocation of 2 billion pesos (about 45 million dollars) for this
year.
</P>
<P>
The funding accounts for about 5 percent of the government's
proposed 73-billion-peso (about 1.66 billion dollars) public
infrastructure spending program for next year, Gullas said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Department of Education, Culture and Sports to
come up with "creative" schemes to address the massive lack of
classrooms,saying the government alone cannot solve the problem on
its own.
</P>
<P>
The department must find ways to involve other sectors, such as
drawing up an adopt-a-school program that would involve the
country's top 1,000 private corporations and leading civic
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The lawmaker also suggested a cost-sharing scheme with selected
local government units in the construction and maintenance of new
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
"We need a deliberate multi-year plan to wipe out the classroom
shortage and give more meaning to the mandate of the constitution
for government to provide free basic education," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
