<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Rabbi's Comment on Holocaust Triggers Anger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Rabbi Ovadia Yosef's
sermon on Saturday, in which he described the six million Jews that
were murdered during the Holocaust as reincarnations of sinners of
the past generations, evoked angry responses on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak said at a government meeting that the
words of the eminent rabbi, who is the spiritual leader of the
ultra-Orthodox Shas party, the third largest political party with
17 seats in the 120-member Knesset (Parliament), are offensive to
many Holocaust survivors and not fitting for a man in his position.
</P>
<P>
Barak added that it is surprising for a party that leads the
social struggle in Israel to say something that hurts the unity of
the Israeli people.
</P>
<P>
In an interview on Israel Radio, Yosef Lapid, leader of the
secular Shinui party, said that these were "in his words he is
confirming Hitler's idea that Jews are sinners." He added that
Rabbi Ovadia Yosef should be kept out of sight from the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg said that there is nothing new in
Yosef's sermon. He argued that the rabbi's statement is based on a
known theological idea and is a way of trying to cope with the
Holocaust on a religious level.
</P>
<P>
President Moshe Katsav expressed the assurance that Rabbi Yosef
felt deeply over the atrocities of the Holocaust. "I'm sure he has
real feelings and suffers daily like every Jew and every person who
has a heart," Katsav said.
</P>
<P>
"The subject of reincarnation is a theological one and I don't
wish to become involved in it, but I regret any remark which hurts
someone's feelings," said the new president who vowed to work for
the unity of the Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
Shas Knesset member Shlomo Benizri said Rabbi Ovadia Yosef does
not mean to hurt anyone with the comment, but to explain the
concept of reincarnation, which according to the former minister of
health, is one of the concepts of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
Benizri also insisted that there are no coalition contacts
between Shas and Barak's ruling One Israel bloc.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the former largest ruling partner in Barak's government,
quit the coalition on the eve of the prime minister's departure for
the July 11-25 Camp David peace summit, for fear that Barak might
make too many concessions to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the party caused a prolonged government crisis with the
left-wing Meretz party over funding for its education network,
which led to the resignation of three ministers from Meretz in late
June.
</P>
<P>
There has been reports saying that Barak is still interested in
bringing Shas back to the shaky government, which now has only 40
seats in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Shas leader Eli Yishai said on Sunday that his party is not
interested in money or in five ministers and therefore it is
unlikely to rejoin the coalition. "We have our red lines," he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that he would agree to meet with Barak, if asked,
but that this would be a matter of good manners and not a desire to
participate in a new government.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Ovadia Yosef criticized Barak for the way in which he
dealt with the Camp David talks. During his weekly sermon on
Saturday, he said, "Barak has no brain and races to reach an
agreement."
</P>
<P>
The rabbi added that he does not trust the Palestinians and
said, "all they want are parts of East Jerusalem and to hurt the
Jews living there."
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Barak's return from the Camp David summit,
however, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef expressed the willingness to rejoin the
coalition, saying that a peace deal that can protect human life is
more important than something that is only of symbolic value.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that sources from Shas predicted Sunday
that Shas will not return to Barak's coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
