<HEADLINE> Indian Air Force MIG-21 Crash Due to Bird Hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Air Force Sunday
said Saturday's crash of its MIG-21, in which the pilot was killed,
was caused by a bird hit.
</P>
<P>
"Initial investigations into the cause of the accident of the
aircraft have shown that there has been a bird hit on the engine
air-intake," an official release said.
</P>
<P>
The bird ingestion could well have caused an engine flame
immediately after the aircraft got airborne, it said, adding that
the pilot had suffered fatal burn injuries.
</P>
<P>
The single-seater plane being piloted by S. C. Shukla, which
crashed at Palam airfield here, was on a ferry flight to
Chandigarh in North India's Punjab State. 
