<HEADLINE> Barak Expects Better Times for Northern Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak told the cabinet on Sunday that he expected a number of
Lebanese security units to arrive at the border with Israel in the
first stage, rather than the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
The units would establish a Lebanese military presence in the
southern part of that country, following the major deployment of
the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) throughout the region
and along the border with Israel on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL troops took up 12 more positions along the northern
border with Lebanon on Saturday, adding to the six outposts manned
last week. The Lebanese government announced that it would send 1,
000 Lebanese soldiers to the area once the United Nations has
completed its deployment.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he expected that a new period of economic development
and increased tourism would now begin in the area along Israel's
northern border.
</P>
<P>
"We have a moral debt to the settlements in the north," Barak
said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Defense Force (IDF) conducted a unilateral pullback
from south Lebanon on May 24, ending its 22-year-long military
occupation of the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the newly-elected President Moshe Katsav will travel
to the north on Sunday afternoon to learn about the impact of the
withdrawal on the residents there and to show solidarity with them.
This will be the first in a series of tours around the country the
president is taking to preach unity and learn the needs of the
people in different sectors.
</P>
<P>
It has taken the United Nations months to verify Israel's
complete withdrawal and draw an international border line between
Israel and Lebanon. 
</P>
