<HEADLINE> Indonesians Gather in Jakarta to Promote Religious Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid Sunday said the country could overcome its present crisis
and eventually become a great nation in the future.
</P>
<P>
"We must maintain the unity and fraternity of our nation and
overcome poverty and backwardness. We are still in a crisis, and
we face threats to our territorial integrity. But we can overcome
this in a short time. We hope we can be a great nation in the
future," the president told the "Indonesia Prays" rally here.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 persons attended the rally to promote religious
harmony, peace and stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
The rally, also attended by House Speaker Akbar Tanjung and
other high-ranking officials, heard representatives of seven
faiths appeal for religious tolerance and peace in the country.
The seven faiths include Islam, Traditional Javanese Belief,
Buddhism, Hinduism, Catholicism, Protestantism and Confucianism.
</P>
<P>
"Plurality is a phenomenon of Indonesia, in the present and in
the future," Akbar said in a brief speech to the gathering.
</P>
<P>
The gathering was held ahead of a critical first annual session
of the People's Consultative Assembly, the country's highest
decision-making body, which is slated to be held from August 7 to
18.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta will be packed by some 66,300 security personnel to
help secure the session and the capital. Some reserve troops have
also been prepared as backup should the situation get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
Security has been tightened further following a bombing last
week that killed two people at the home of the Philippine
ambassador here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, communal violence between Christians and Muslims has
broken out in several regions in Indonesia in the past months,
including Maluku, North Maluku, Central Sulawesi and Central
Kalimantan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is one of the world's largest Muslim-populated
countries with about 88 percent of its 210 million people
following Islam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
