<HEADLINE> Manila Warns Traders Not to Manipulate Sugar Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government warned
unscrupulous traders over the weekend not to manipulate the price
of sugar in the local market as it prepares to import some 150,000
metric tons of sugar.
</P>
<P>
Director General Felipe Medalla of the National Economic and
Development Authority said in a radio interview that the
government expects imported sugar from Thailand and Australia to
come in a month's time.
</P>
<P>
"Speculators, you will lose money because the National Food
Authority will bring in 150,000 metric tons of sugar," she said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Trade and Industry Undersecretary Ernesto Ordonez, who
also heads the country's price control council, issued a warning
to unscrupulous sugar traders that they will be dealt with
accordingly if found hoarding sugar to artificially jack up their
prices.
</P>
<P>
The price of sugar has risen sharply in some places in the
country and the government blamed this on traders' hoarding
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
