<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Three members of the Red Cross and
Red Crescent mission in Tbilisi, capital of Georgia, were missing
on Friday in the country's north mountains near the border with
Russia's rebel republic of Chechnya, Russian Media reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The three, a Georgian, an Italian and a French national,
traveling in a Toyota car to the village of Dausi in Georgia's
Akhmeta region for humanitarian work, were believed to have been
missing after losing contact with their base for 24 hours, the
Interfax news agency quoted Akhmeta district police as saying.
</P>
<P>
Police have found the car with the their identification cards
and personal things at the roadside near the village of Omalo,
which is on the Chechen stretch of the Georgian-Russian border.
The car was not damaged, but the walkie-talkie did not work,
Interfax cited the Georgian Interior Ministry as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian was identified as the driver Yuri Darchiyev and
the other two were women, French national Sophie Prokofiev and
Italian Natalie Zelino. They were going to study the situation of
several thousand Chechen refugees settled in the valley for the
purpose of rendering humanitarian aid to them, according to the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Georgian law enforcement agencies did not rule out
the possibility that the Red Cross workers may have been taken
hostage.
</P>
<P>
The Tbilisi office of the Red Cross and Red Crescent has also
confirmed the disappearance of their employees, but has not made
any comments on the incident.
</P>
<P>
Search for the missing is still going on, said the Georgian
Interior Ministry. 
</P>
