<HEADLINE> Israeli Military Asks for More Funds to Cope With Possible Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Force (IDF)
called on the treasury at the weekend to reimburse it with 1
billion shekels (about 250 million U.S. dollars) that were cut from
last year's budget to cope with possible clashes, Ha'aretz daily
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli defense and intelligence analysts have predicted that
uncertainties will reign on both the Palestinian and Lebanese
fronts between September and December, when the Palestinians are
expected to declare an independent statehood.
</P>
<P>
The chances for a successful diplomatic deal that will prevent
any outburst of violence depend, to a great extent, on the
development in the domestic political sphere, observed the paper.
</P>
<P>
The IDF's general staff is holding two days of sessions this
week to discuss planning and operation assessments in the event of
renewed tensions on the Palestinian front following the declaration
of a Palestinian state. Also on the agenda is IDF's budget for
2001.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that top IDF analysts believe that without a
peace deal with the Palestinians and increased U.S. aid, the
military will face an "insufferable" gap between its tasks and its
readiness.
</P>
<P>
This gap would require a reduction in manpower, cutbacks in
training exercises and closing down some long-term projects.
</P>
<P>
However, IDF senior officers said the unexpected rise in the
country's revenues from tax collection has enabled the government
to refund the military establishment the money that was cut from
last year's defense budget.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, said the paper, Military Intelligence doubts
whether the Arab and Islamic world would back any flexibility in
the Palestinian position on Jerusalem, a sticking point that led to
the collapse of the July 11-25 Camp David peace summit.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted General Staff sources as saying that
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will try to prolong the
negotiations with Israel either until the end of the year, or until
there is a significant change in Israel's domestic political scene,
such as new elections or the opposition Likud faction joining the
government.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is facing an urgent and uphill
task of reshuffling his government, which has shrunk to a minority
of 40 seats in the 120-member Knesset (parliament) with the
resignations of ruling coalition partners due to differences over
the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In either case, said the intelligence officers, Arafat might
unilaterally declare a Palestinian state, ready to enter into a
conflict that would also include clashes on the northern border
with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On the assumption that even without an agreement, the Camp David
summit enabled a mapping of those areas that would be annexed to
Israel or are considered vital for its defense interests, the army
will be able to focus on defending these areas.
</P>
<P>
If the Palestinians settle for practical sovereignty over Areas
A and B, which they already control, the situation may become
similar to that existing on the northern border after the IDF's
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon on May 24, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
But until all these issues are clarified by events, the IDF will
remain in a state of alert, ready to be called into action on both
fronts in case of a rapid deterioration in the situation, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
