<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed on exchanges of
media organizations in order to help implement the June 15 Joint
Declaration signed by the leaders of two sides in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached when the South Korea's media
delegation consisting of 46 presidents of newspapers and TV
stations met with DPRK officials in the Mansudae Assembly Hall in
Pyongyang Sunday morning, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the two sides shared a consensus on the
importance of the media's role in the process of promoting inter-
Korean reconciliation, national unity and, ultimately, unification,
report said.
</P>
<P>
On the principle of inter-Korean media exchanges, they agreed
to form a committee to make an agreement on detailed steps of
media exchanges during the South Korean delegation's stay in
Pyongyang. The South Korean delegation arrived in Pyongyang last
Saturday for a eight-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, South Korean Culture and Tourism Minister
Park Jie-won, who led the delegation, conveyed President Kim Dae-
jung's invitation of DPRK press group to visit South Korea. The
DPRK side has accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean media group is expected to meet with DPRK
leader Kim Jong Il, who invited them to the DPRK during his
historic summit with President Kim on June 13-15 this year.
</P>
