<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Vehemently Condemns U.N. For Decade-Old Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council has been committing a crime of genocide against the Iraqi
people during the past 10 years, an editorial carried by the
official daily Baghdad Observer said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"For 10 years, the U.N. Security Council is committing genocide
in Iraq under flimsy pretexts and changing conditions," said the
editorial, adding that the sanctions have been going on without any
respect to the U.N. Charter, international laws and norms.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.N. Charter were to be respected, U.N. officials and
the Security Council should be charged with the premeditated crime
of genocide and brought to court of justice," the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
It is no surprise that Iraq is in a fury as it has been
subjected to the toughest sanctions in history, and the end of
sanctions is yet to be seen.
</P>
<P>
Sunday marks the 10th anniversary of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq:
On August 6, 1990, four days after Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait, the
U.N. Security Council passed the Resolution 661 and imposed
stringent sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says that as many as 1.3 million people, mostly children
and the elderly, have died of curable diseases as a direct result
of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The decade-old sanctions have proved that the U.N. Security
Council is "a mere tool to the United States strategy," said the
editorial.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., as a leading member of the U.N. Security Council, has
been behind the continuation of sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, 70 members of the U.S. House of Representatives have
sent a letter to President Bill Clinton, arguing that the sanctions
have inflicted suffering on ordinary Iraqis, the editorial noted.
</P>
<P>
The editorial also accused Kuwait of being "a spearhead to the
U.S. conspiracy against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Al-Sabah said on July 25
that only stronger military and economic ties with Washington would
safeguard the emirate against a repeat of Iraqis invasion.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait rejects any direct dialog with Iraqi officials until
Baghdad frees all Kuwaiti prisoners of war (POWs) still held since
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait claims that Iraq still holds some 600 Kuwaiti POWs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
