<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-oil Sector in UAE to Play Major Role in Propelling Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The non-oil sector in the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) is expected to contribute to 72 percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP) in the next two years, the
Dubai-based Gulf News daily Sunday quoted economists as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Non-oil sectors can expect overall nominal growth of at least
five percent a year over the forecast period. This will raise their
share of GDP to 72 percent in 2002, from 70 percent in 2000," the
paper quoted a report of the third quarter forecast on UAE's
economy as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was issued by the Britain-based Business
Monitor International, also said Dubai is forced by its limited oil
reserves to step up its diversification plans, while tourism, e-
commerce and other sectors are targeted for faster development.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications sector is expected to jump by 10 percent
this year, fuelled by the establishment of the Dubai Internet City
(SIC) and the rising demand for telecommunications facilities
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The report added the construction, trade and transport and
communications sectors will expect a rebound due to recovery in
government spending and improvement in international trade
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Construction and real estate will grow by five percent this year
following a two-year shake-off as projects that were once shelved
now start to be developed in Abu Dhabi and Dubai.
</P>
<P>
The much-delayed project of corporate headquarters for the Abu
Dhabi Investment Authority, for instance, has finally gone out to
tender, pushing the prestigious 200 million U.S. dollars project on
stream.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, power and water and financial services will
continue to prosper though some problems are expected at the stock
market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
