<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denies Offering Ransom to Abu Sayyaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanon diplomat in Manila
denies local press reports Sunday that the Libyan government has
offered 25 million U.S. dollars in ransom to Abu Sayyaf for the
release of the hostages held in the southern Philippine province
of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's vice consul to Manila, Joseph Assad, said there is no
truth in the reports that Seif Al-Islam, son of Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi, had sent an emissary to Manila to work out the
deal, the local ABS-CBN news channel reported.
</P>
<P>
Reports earlier surfaced that Libya is ready to pay a ransom of
25 million dollars to the Muslim extremist group Abu Sayyaf to
gain the freedom of 29 hostages, and that Seif Al-Islam has sent
an emissary to the Philippine capital to try for a deal.
</P>
<P>
The reports, quoting a report of the Lebanese daily An-Nahar,
said the envoy Mohamed Ismail contacted the Lebanese embassy in
Tokyo and expressed "full readiness" to pay one million dollars
for the release of Marie Moarbes, a Lebanese-Frenh, as first
priority.
</P>
<P>
Ismail also reportedly told the Lebanese mission that Libya is
willing to pay 24 million dollars more for the rest captives.
</P>
<P>
The 29 hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf in Jolo island, Sulu,
include the remaining 14 of the 21 hostages kidnapped from
Malaysia's Sipadan island on April 23 -- three Malaysians, two
Germans, two French nationals, two Finns, two South Africans, Two
Filipinos and the Lebanese-French woman.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf rebels are also holding three French TV
journalists who went to Jolo to cover the hostage crisis and 12
Filipino Christian evangelists who went there to pray for the
hostages early July.
</P>
<P>
So far, the rebels have released six Malaysians and one German
woman of the Sipadan group, one German journalist, two Filipino
reporters and one Christian evangelist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
