<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Police Seize Largest Illicit Drug Cache </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's anti-narcotics police have
seized 35-million-dollar-worth of hallucinogenic drugs and arrested
six suspects in the largest haul of illegal drugs in the kingdom's
history, the semiofficial Jordan Times reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Acting on tips, the narcotics squad confiscated 3,341,400
tablets of Captagon with a potential black market value of 24
million Jordanian dinars (35 million U.S. dollars) and three
Kalashnikov rifles from the six suspects, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
One of the suspects is a Jordanian citizen, but police refused
to disclose the nationalities of the other five under police
custody.
</P>
<P>
Police stashed the cache of pills in a secluded cave near the
Al Hassa district, more than 200 kilometers south of the capital
city Amman.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations revealed the drugs were destined for
a neighboring Arab country which police refused to name.
</P>
<P>
The seizure came four months after police busted a similar drug
trafficking operation, in which 107 kilograms of heroin worth 10.5
million dollars were intercepted by police on the Jordanian-Syrian
border.
</P>
<P>
Most of illegal drugs passing through Jordan usually find their
way to Israel, Egypt and the Gulf states, notably Saudi Arabia,
Jordan
Times said.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom has been used as major transit point in recent years
by international drug traffickers, who ship narcotics made in
Eastern countries and former Soviet Union states to the Gulf, Egypt
and Israel via Turkey, Syria and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian police seized 201 kilograms of heroin between the
years of 1996 to 1999 alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
