<HEADLINE> United Airlines Cuts 156 Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 5 (Xinhua) -- United Airlines, the world's
largest carrier, canceled more than 150 flights at Chicago's
O'Hare International Airport on Saturday because of crew shortages
and bad weather, the company said.
</P>
<P>
United pilots have refused to work overtime since their
contract expired in April, said United Airlines spokesman Chris
Brathwaite. The company and the pilots' union are negotiating a
contract with a federal mediator and hope to have a new agreement
in place by early September.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we had about 156 United flights canceled today because of
a combination of weather and crew shortages," said Brathwaite. "We
are trying to get people diverted to other planes."
</P>
<P>
The sticking points are job security, flight assignments,
salary and benefits. Negotiations between the two sides became
more complicated when United Airlines announced earlier this year
that it planned to acquire U.S. Airways, the No. 6 U.S. carrier.
</P>
<P>
Thunderstorms and showers moved into the Midwest this weekend.
Weather problems on the East Coast have contributed to the
cancellations, Brathwaite added.
</P>
<P>
United Airlines has about 960 flights per day out of O'Hare.
Industry sources noted that Saturday's cancellations totaled about
half of the airline's cancellations systemwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
