<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Relay SEA Anti-Tobacco Flame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is preparing for the
conveyance of the Southeast Asian (SEA) Anti-Tobacco Flame under
an anti-tobacco movement being launched by the World Health
Organization (WHO), official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, a member of the WHO, is among countries in the SEA
region where the anti-tobacco flame is to be relayed.
</P>
<P>
A three-week activities will be coupled while the flame is kept
in Myanmar, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar is taking measures to control tobacco and
conduct tobacco-free activities in the wake of the alarming stage
of smoking condition reached in the country in terms of the number
of smokers, the amount of tobacco and age of smokers.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows that 47 percent of the adults in Myanmar were
smokers in the 1990s with youths between 10 and 20 years of age
smoking in one way or another in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimate of the WHO, an adult smoker in Myanmar
consumes 2,000 to 3,000 cigarettes per year. 
</P>
