<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring of Thai Key Economic Ministries Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A meeting of economic ministers, held here this week, agreed
that the three key economic ministries, including industry,
commerce, and agriculture and cooperatives, needed to complete
their respective restructuring plans within six months, Minister
to the Prime Minister's Office Abhisit Vejajiva said in the report.
</P>
<P>
Once the restructuring plans are completed, the Ministry of
Commerce will change its name to the Ministry of International
Trade and Industry (MITI), like the Japanese MITI, to be in charge
of all trade transactions with foreign countries, as well as
negotiations under the framework of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC), and of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), he
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Currently, negotiations under the APEC framework are under the
supervision of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs; while those under
the AFTA are within the responsibility of the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
All jobs relating to farmers would then be transformed to the
Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives, and a new independent
agency would be established to be in charge of the insurance
industry; while the work of consumers' protection would then be
under the supervision of the Ministry to Prime Minister's Office,
instead of the Ministry of Commerce, said Abhisit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Deputy PM on Trade with, Investment in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral trade between Myanmar
and Thailand is progressing well in spite of the fact that both
countries' economies suffered from certain crisis in the last
couple of years, said Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with the press at the end of the second session of the
Myanmar-Thai Joint Trade Commission (JTC) here Saturday evening,
Supachai noted that like last year, the positive trade expansion
for some years exceeded 20 percent, pointing out that highly
commendable improvement was brought about which is tremendous jump
in the export from Myanmar to Thailand of more than 76 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
It helps to narrow the gap of trade between the two countries,
he said, hoping to see that the bilateral trade be more balanced.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has large surplus in trade with Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
He believes that there will be more import demand of goods from
Myanmar to Thailand, emphasizing that the Thai government has
placed the highest priority to cross-border trade with Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Thailand has set up a Cross-Border Trade
Promotion Committee, which he chairs.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for both sides to improve the payment
system and banking relations to expedite the implementation of
banking agreements and memorandums of understanding signed in the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
He recommends more banks to be involved in the MOUs in addition
to the existing only one Thai bank in the banking process dealing
with the private sector of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand would help Myanmar solve its trade deficit
which is likely brought about by allowing more open trade.
</P>
<P>
On investment, Supachai went on to say that Thailand encourages
more Thai investment into Myanmar, saying that Thailand is now the
third largest investor in the country and agreeing that there
would be more rooms for investment between the two countries. At
the moment Thailand is on the verge of signing an agreement on
investment promotion and protection, especially in the areas of
propagation of seeds for various types of agricultural products
and agro-industry.
</P>
<P>
As to tourism, he said Thailand would help Myanmar promote
tourist in-flow by upgrading coastal Dawei area in Southern part
of the country to a tourist spot.
</P>
<P>
With regard to fishery, he said that Thailand has been
providing assistance to Myanmar in the marine shrimp propagation
project until its completion, adding that the implementation has
been quite successful.
</P>
<P>
The two-day second session of the Myanmar-Thai JTC, which began
on Friday, was attended by Myanmar delegation, led by Commerce
Minister Brigadier-General Pyi Sone, and its Thai counterpart,
headed by Supachai who arrived here on Thursday for the session.
</P>
</TEXT>
