<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
Most of the newspapers front-paged the story that Chinese
President Jiang Zemin met with six world well-known scientists in
the seaside resort of Beidaihe, about 300 kilometers east of
Beijing, Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang said that in the intense international
competition, China is facing an arduous task of improving its
economic structure, making rational use of resources, protecting
the ecological environment, promoting rational development between
different regions, improving the quality of its population and
doing all it can to completely eliminate poverty.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
--South China's Guangdong Province reported a continuous
economic development in the first half of the year, and the
province leads the country in terms of income generated by state-
run enterprises and in terms of foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, the province accomplished 406.2
billion yuan in gross domestic product (GDP), up 10.6 percent from
the same period last year. The province exported 42.8 billion U.S.
dollars of commodities in the six-month period, up 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
--Heilongjiang Province, an old industrial base in northeast
China, completed 132.03 billion yuan in GDP in the first six
months, up 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector generated 59.58 billion yuan in added
value during the January-June period, up 11.5 percent. The growth
rate is higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
--After more than a dozen years' efforts, Xi'an Translation
College of northwest China's Shaanxi Province has grown into the
country's largest non-state-run institution of higher learning in
China. It now has 17,000 students and a total of 300 million yuan
in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
--Science and technology is more and more widely used in
growing trees and grass to hold back sand movements in northwest
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region as scientific progress not
only reduces the cost to combat sand, but also brings about better
results.
</P>
<P>
--Starting from this month, more than 100,000 medical workers
in southwest China's Chongqing municipality will have to work
under contracts, bidding farewell to "iron rice bowl" -- secure
employment in disregard of work performances.
</P>
<P>
--South China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region finds itself
in a new round of port construction drive. Experts estimate that
more than 400 berths with 10,000 DWT (dead weight tonnage) each
can be built along the coastline in Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
--China's oil sector has no reason to be overly optimistic,
although it reported great achievements during the first half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
--Chinese trade experts have improved their outlook for this
year's bilateral trade between China and the Republic of Korea (
ROK). Xu Changwen, director of the Asian and African Studies
Department of the China Academy of International Trade and
Economic Cooperation, predicted the trade between China and ROK
would reach 30 billion U.S. dollars this year, judging from trade
between the two countries during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
--China's textile exports to the United States rose 32.1
percent to 2.64 billion U.S. dollars during the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
--Demand for employees by Chinese enterprises has been
recovering since the beginning of this year, thanks to the country
's improve macroeconomy.
</P>
<P>
--China's thriving marine industry has become a powerful force
in the economy. The output value of the marine industry is
expected to make up at least five percent of the country's gross
domestic product his year, said Chen Qingtai, deputy director of
the Development Research Center under the State Council. 
</P>
