<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing Universities Enrolls More Students from Taiwan, Macao,
Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
The top 43 universities in this national capital enrolled 564
postgraduate students for the Autumn semester from Hong Kong,
Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The universities include the prestigious Beijing University and
Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Among the students, 146 are from Hong Kong, 278 from Macao and
140 from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and thirty-seven of them are enrolled in doctoral
courses, an increase of 53.9 percent from last year. The other 427
are enrolled in masters courses, up 59.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
School-Run Science Parks Develop Smoothly in China
</P>
<P>
Fifteen university-based science parks have been developing
smoothly in China over the past year.
</P>
<P>
This was learned at a national conference on university-run
science parks in Wuhan, the provincial capital of central Hubei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Science and Technology and the
Ministry of Education stressed the importance of these science
parks in promoting the integration of science and technology,
education and the economy.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua University to Have More CPC members among Young
Teachers
</P>
<P>
About 140 young teachers in China 's prestigious Qinghua
University have recently applied for the membership of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), as part of the university's
efforts to cultivate excellent youth.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 young teachers joined the CPC between 1994 and 1998.
The university sources noted that young teachers not only take the
responsibility of training successors of the socialist system, but
they are the successors themselves, and will greatly influence the
development and future of Qinghua.  
</P>
