<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major environment news stories Xinhua released from July 31 to
August 4:
</P>
<P>
60 Billion Yuan For Bohai Sea Environment Protection
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will set aside 60 billion yuan (7.23
billion U.S. dollars) into the ecological environment protection
of the Bohai Sea area within the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jirong, deputy director of the State Environment
Protection Administration (SEPA), said that the project aims to
control the epicontinental pollution, improve and restore nearby
habitats, and better administer the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
The project will be implemented in three five-year phases
starting from this year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Enterprises Meet Environmental Standards
</P>
<P>
All industrial enterprises in China will meet national
standards of waste disposal by the end of the year, an
environmental official said in Qingdao on July 31.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jirong, deputy director of the State Environmental
Protection Administration said that 86 percent of Chinese
enterprises have met national requirements of pollution control.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Chinese government has adopted powerful
measures to control the discharge of waste on land to protect the
marine eco-system.
</P>
<P>
Grain-For-Green Project Will Cause No Grain Shortages: Experts
</P>
<P>
Chinese agricultural experts said that the large-scale
returning of low-yielding farmland to forests and grassland in
western area will cause no grain shortages in China.
</P>
<P>
Under the government-initiated "grain-for-green" program, China
's resource-rich, economically backward hinterland is expected to
be afforested with trees and grass in the upcoming decades.
</P>
<P>
Successive grain harvests over the past few years have provided
a solid foundation for the "grain-for-green" project that is
currently being carried out in China's vast western regions.
</P>
<P>
China Stepping Up Treatment of Water Pollution
</P>
<P>
China is taking positive measures to fight against water
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA) plans
to strengthen the control on enterprises that discharge pollutants
and accelerate the construction of sewage-treating plants.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources vows to reinforce the
supervision on water quality and make drinking water reach state
standards.
</P>
<P>
Some 131 waste water disposal factories are still needed in the
rivers of Huaihe, Haihe and Liaohe and the lakes of Taihu, Dianchi
and Chaohu. At present there are already 28 such factories in
operation while 125 are under construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000806.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Worsening Water Pollution Causes Big Hazard
</P>
<P>
Deteriorating water pollution in China will do great harm to
people's health and life quality, according to some members of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
Since some areas and rivers around Chinese cities are being
polluted, ground water could become toxic and unsuitable for human
consumption, the Subcommittee of Human Resources and Environment
of CPPCC warned at a recent symposium on "drinking water and
health" in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Effective Control of Desertification in Anhui
</P>
<P>
East China's Anhui Province has effectively turned more than
100,000 ha. of arid and desertified land into vegetated areas in
the past decades.
</P>
<P>
As a result, greenery has so far covered 32.4 percent of local
arid and desertified land, whose grain yield has grown by 10 to 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
The province has some 700,000 ha. of arid and desertified land,
mostly in northern Anhui. Of them, 130,000 ha. are desertified
land, which pose a big threat to local ecological environment and
hamper local economic development.
</P>
<P>
Dangshan County, which suffers from serious drifting sand in
the province, has done a good work in controlling shifting sand,
growing trees and grass, and developing agricultural production in
desertified areas in the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide Ecologists Eye on Changbai Mountains
</P>
<P>
Research fellows from Taiwan, China's mainland, U.S., Canada
and Austria have cooperated in the research of soil, hydrology,
meteorology and zoology in the Changbai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
Changbai mountains in north east China's Jilin Province is well
known as an "international genepool of species" and an area with
the most intact ecological system internationally featured by over
70 species of trees, 90 kinds of ferns, over 1,250 species of
plants, some 50 species of wild beasts, more than 200 kinds of
birds and some 1,000 kinds of insects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
