<HEADLINE> Tunisia, Libya Reaffirm Promotion of Dialog among Maghreb Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Tunisian and Libyan leaders have
stressed the importance of promoting dialog between Arab Maghreb
Union and other regional and international groups, including the
European Union, on equal footing.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a joint communique issued at the end of
Libyan leader Muammar Ghaddafi's three-day working visit to
Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, both Ghaddafi and Tunisian President Zine el
Abidine Ben Ali expressed the hope to achieve common interests of
both the Maghred Union, or UMA, and the EU through dialog.
</P>
<P>
The UMA, created in 1989, groups five African nations of
Algeria, Libya, Mauritania, Morocco and Tunisia. It has been
paralyzed since five years ago, mainly due to disagreement between
Algeria and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Ghaddafi and Ben Ali also hoped that security, peace, stability
and fruitful cooperation can be achieved among the Mediterranean
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the need to convene an urgent Arab summit,
and to hold such a summit regularly.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the Libyan leader met three times with Ben Ali
to discuss bilateral ties and an agreement on upgrading bilateral
trade volume from the present 700 million U.S. dollars to 1 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On his way back to Libya by road Saturday, Ghaddafi visited the
grave of former Tunisian President Habib Bourguiba, the founder of
modern Tunisia who died in April, in the town of Monastir, 140
kilometers (80 miles) southeast of Tunis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
