<HEADLINE> Iran Says No Change towards Afghan Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran declared on Sunday that it
would not have a change of heart towards the Afghan Taliban militia
as long as they have not punished those responsible for the 1998
killing of Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The statement came on the eve of the second anniversary of the
Taliban attack on the Iranian consulate in Mazari Sharif in
northern Afghanistan on August 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Eight Iranian diplomats and a reporter were killed by the
militiamen. Iran has been demanding that the Taliban find out and
punish those responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Iran is following up its demand at the United Nations and the
government had renewed its petition with the world organization on
Sunday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi was quoted by
the state-run IRNA news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the Taliban militia, which controls
over 90 percent of the Afghan territory, have improved despite
Tehran's continued support for the ousted government of President
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Asefi expressed hope that the rivaling Afghan factions would
respect their pledges at talks and work to put an end to their
decade-old civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
