<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 400 Refugees in Tanzania to Resettle in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada will resettle a
total of 400 refugees residing in western Tanzanian camps to its
Quebec Province within this year.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugee (UNHCR) Branch Office here said Monday that the first
batch of 180 refugees will be airlifted from Mwanza airport
Tuesday directly to Quebec.
</P>
<P>
The rest is scheduled to leave the refugee camps by the end of
this year with the help of the International Organization for
Migration (IOM) contracted by UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, most of whom from Burundi and the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), have lived for years in the camps
after fleeing wars in the central African countries.
</P>
<P>
IOM will run a cultural orientation course for the refugees who
are considered by the UNHCR most in need of protection and with
little hope of returning to their countries of origin. Among the
criteria used by the Canadian Immigration Services in selecting
the refugees to be resettled is the ability to integrate well into
Canadian society.
</P>
<P>
"The head of the family in nearly every case speaks French and
has either finished High School or University education," the
release said.
</P>
<P>
Some of them are families with one spouse being ethnic Tutsi
and the other being ethnic Hutu, or in mixed marriage, a target
for prosecution by both ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR officials said that there are some 400,000 refugees in
western Tanzania from neighboring Burundi, the DRC, Rwanda and
Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
