<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Resume Amid Major Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Heads of 19 Burundian
parties began a new round of peace talks in northern Tanzanian
town of Arusha on Monday to try to resolve outstanding differences
on a draft peace agreement expected to be signed on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Burundi government and Hutu rebel groups
are also expected to hold talks with the peace facilitator and
former South African President Nelson Mandela in South Africa this
week.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Arusha said that the tough negotiations come as
both the Burundian government and the rebels have expressed strong
reservations about the peace plan that was presented to them by
Mandela last month.
</P>
<P>
Delegates would focus on cease-fire arrangement, the leadership
of a transitional government, integration of the rebels into the
Tutsi-led armed forces, the proposed electoral system, and the
treatment of political prisoners in the week-long closed-door
talks.
</P>
<P>
"Mandela has told them that the draft agreement will not be
changed unless all the parties reach a consensus," an official of
the facilitation team said.
</P>
<P>
The two main armed rebel groups, CNDD-FDD and PALIPEHUTU-FNL,
have indicated they will not sign the document until certain
conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
PALIPEHUTU-FNL refused to attend the last round of negotiations
in Arusha at which CNDD-FDD was present for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The current wrangling has prompted many observers to note that
the signing ceremony, scheduled for August 28, now hangs in the
balance, although Mandela insisted that the date will be adhered
to.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, sources close to the mediation team said that the
question of who will lead the transitional government in Burundi
is the most intractable issue facing the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft proposals, the Tutsi minority, which has
dominated Burundi since independence, would hand over power to a
democratically elected government in three years' time after the
appointment of a transitional government.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi conflict between Tutsi-dominated government troops
and Hutu rebels has cost 200,000 lives since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya recently warned of a
premature signing of a peace agreement, saying a cease-fire must
come into effect before any accord is signed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
