<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) summit meeting in Windhoek, Namibia,
went into overtime on Monday afternoon as they wrestled with key
issues including the wars in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) and Angola and the restructuring of the organization.
</P>
<P>
According to South African Press Association, the heads of
state were originally due to end their closed session at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister of the DRC Abdoulaye Yerodia told
reporters during an earlier break that the leaders have decided to
hold a special meeting in Lusaka on August 14 to discuss the
conflict in his country.
</P>
<P>
On Monday afternoon, the summit meeting also discussed
proposals for restructuring SADC, including a move to bring its
controversial security organ firmly under central control.
</P>
<P>
The SADC council of ministers, which met on Friday and Saturday,
has recommended that the issue be held over, but South Africa
pressed on Monday for a decision on at least the reform of the
security organ.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state are also due to formally approve the revised
SADC free trade agreement, which is scheduled for implementation
on September 1. 
