<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Invest $40 Billion in Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, the biggest oil-producing
country in Africa, plans to invest 40 billion U.S. dollars into
the oil industry within the next five years to consolidate the oil
sector as the country's biggest revenue earner, local media
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Aboki Zawa, Permanent Secretary in the newly-established
Ministry of Petroleum Resources, disclosed the plan in the capital
Abuja at the weekend while signing the revised memorandum of
understanding with its joint venture partners in the country's oil
sector.
</P>
<P>
Zawa said the government would spend about 8 billion dollars
annually to intensify its efforts in oil exploration, adding that
the government has mapped out a concrete plan to facilitate the
investment.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the sixth largest oil exporting country in the world,
produces more than two million barrels of crude daily. Its
earnings from oil export accounts for more than 95 percent of the
country's revenue, with the average monthly earning exceeding 1
billion dollars. 
</P>
