<HEADLINE> Zambia Ready to Ratify SADC Trade Protocol: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is ready to
ratify the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) Trade
Protocol at this week's SADC Heads of State Summit in Namibia
after some contentious issues in the treaty are ironed out, the
Zambia Daily Mail reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
William Harrington, Minister for Commerce, Trade and Industry,
was quoted as saying in an interview before departure on Sunday
that most thorny issues in the protocol had been ironed out and
his ministry was waiting for cabinet approval before ratification.
</P>
<P>
The issues included the non-conclusion of negotiations on the
specific rules of origin, which would determine the origination of
a product, the non-existence of dispute settlement mechanisms and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Harrington said treatment of non-tariff barriers and non-
conclusion of special arrangement in market access for sugar,
textile and clothing were also serious issues Zambia had raised.
</P>
