<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Reduce Inflation Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian central bank will try
to reduce the inflation rate from the current 25.9 percent to 19
percent by the end of this year to stimulate investor confidence,
Times of Zambia reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kabinga Pande, head of public relations of the Bank of Zambia,
was quoted by the paper as saying on Sunday that Zambia's broad
macro-economic objectives are to attain a real Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) growth of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The key to bring down inflation is a firm control over the
growth of money supply and credit in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The bank will ensure that the growth in money supply and credit
is neither insufficient nor excessive, but adequate to facilitate
economic and financial transactions needed for a sound economic
growth, Pande said.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank will limit the domestic fiscal deficit to 2.3
percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The bank will make concerted efforts to further lower and
stabilize inflation through extensive use of market based monetary
policy, said Pande. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
