seditious material, Zambia National Broadcasting Corporation
reported.
</P>
<P>
The policemen, launching the operation at 4:00 a.m. (local time)
, did not allow anyone to enter into the residence of Mwila, who
was also the National Treasurer of the country's ruling Movement
for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD).
</P>
<P>
Mwila, in a interview with Zambia National Broadcasting
Corporation Sunday evening, said that about 100 policemen left his
residence at 14:00 p.m. (local time) without taking anything from
his home.
</P>
<P>
However, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said he has no
information on the reported police action and can not comment on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
Mwila lost his ministerial portfolio early last month days
after he was expelled from MMD on a charge of involvement in anti-
party activities.
</P>
<P>
Mwila announced his candidature for the MMD presidency on May
26 in a bid to run for the country's presidency in the general
elections to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, one of the country's richest magnates, helped incumbent
President Chiluba defeat former President Kenneth Kaunda in the
1991 elections. He is seen as one of the leading candidates to
replace Chiluba in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
But Chiluba has indicated that he would ensue that Mwila does
not become the president and those who start the election campaign
for the MMD presidency prematurely will be punished. 
