<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Provide Fees for Pipeline Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
considering to pay local communities in the southern oil-producing
states to protect oil pipelines running through their villages.
</P>
<P>
Communities in the oil-producing areas should be encouraged to
guard the pipelines, even if they have to be paid, said Nigerian
Information Minister Jerry Gana in Enugu, capital of Enugu state
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Last month pipeline explosions in the country's oil-producing
states, caused by vandalizations of local communities to steal
fuel after having punctured the pipelines, claimed several hundred
lives.
</P>
<P>
The government blamed the explosions on illegal activities of
corrupt officials in the state-run fuel companies, while the fuel
companies complained that local villagers tap into the pipelines
to siphon off fuel or crude oil to sell to the black market.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the biggest oil-producing country in Africa, produces
more than 2 million barrels of crude oil daily, accounting for
more than 90 percent of the country's revenue. 
</P>
