<HEADLINE> SADC Govts not Able to Allow Free Movement Across Borders: Chissano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The governments of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) can not allow free
movement of business people across borders, outgoing SADC Chairman
Joachim Chissano said at the Windhoek summit meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the region is vulnerable to drug, arms trafficking
and car theft, Chissano, also Mozambican President, said keeping
gates open 24 hours will require trained staff.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks when Elias Dewah, executive director of
Botswana's Federation of Commerce, urged Southern African leaders
to open border posts 24 hours a day to give a better protection of
visitors and allow free movement of business people in the region
at a dialogue between SADC heads of state and regional business
people at the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue was followed by the signing of a memorandum of
understanding between the SADC Secretariat and the SADC
Association of Chambers of Commerce and Industry which is the
first formal recognition of the relationship between the two
organizations. 
</P>
