<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agencies Appeal for Food Aid to Kenyan Famine Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen humanitarian groups in
Kenya Monday blamed the international community for responding
inadequately to the Kenyan government and the World Food Program's
appeal for 88-million U.S. dollars worth of relief food to over 3
million Kenyans facing starvation as a result of long drought.
</P>
<P>
The groups said in a statement that the food shortages are
becoming desperate in the country and so far only a third of the
requirements have been committed.
</P>
<P>
"There is a serious shortfall for August. There is neither the
food nor the money for us to meet the huge needs we face in the
worst affected regions," said Emma Naylor, emergency program
coordinator for Oxfam Great Britain, which is delivering food in
Wajir and Turkana districts in northeastern and northern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's drought and food shortages are part of a wider problems
in the Horn of Africa, Naylor warned, "we can't wait until this
crisis becomes a catastrophe, and we have to act now to end this
vicious cycle of sufferings."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the aid groups called for more support from
donors to long-term solutions .
</P>
<P>
"We need food to address the immediate needs, but we also need
a commitment to support recovery programs when the drought is over,
" said Edward Ontito, an official from the Adventist Development
and Relief Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
